# Security

Apply these expectations when adding or changing code anywhere in the repo.

## XSS and untrusted content

- Avoid `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` and raw HTML strings for user-controlled or file-loaded content unless there is an explicit, reviewed sanitization path.
- Treat text labels, imported documents, and pasted content as untrusted; prefer rendering as plain text or existing safe pipelines (not arbitrary HTML/SVG script vectors).

## URLs and navigation

- Do not open external URLs from unvalidated strings. Reject or normalize dangerous schemes (`javascript:`, `data:` where inappropriate).
- For `window.open` / `<a target="_blank">`, use `rel="noopener noreferrer"` (or equivalent) where applicable.

## Files, clipboard, and JSON

- `.excalidraw` / scene JSON / import paths: validate structure, cap size and depth where practical; never execute code embedded in data.
- Clipboard paste: do not treat pasted HTML/XML as safe without the same guarantees as the rest of the app.

## Secrets and configuration

- Do not commit API keys, tokens, or private endpoints. Use environment variables and CI secrets (Firebase, Sentry, collab backends, etc.).
- Do not log secrets, session tokens, or unnecessary PII in client-side logs or analytics.

## Dependencies and supply chain

- No new npm packages without explicit approval (see architecture rules). Prefer audited, maintained dependencies for security-sensitive code paths.

## Realtime and backends

- Do not trust messages from Socket.io / Firebase / other network channels without validation and expected auth/session rules aligned with the backend design.

## Infrastructure (when touching Docker / nginx / HTML entry)

- Prefer secure defaults: tight CSP where feasible, sensible `Referrer-Policy`, avoid framing clickjacking unless intentionally allowed (`X-Frame-Options` / `frame-ancestors`).
- Do not expose extra ports or debug endpoints in production-oriented configs without an explicit reason.

For data loading and restore specifics, see `security-data-restore.mdc`. For the app shell (env, collab, PWA), see `security-excalidraw-app.mdc`.

## How to verify

- Review changes for `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`, raw HTML from user/file data, unvalidated URLs, and missing `rel="noopener noreferrer"` on `target="_blank"` links.
- Grep for accidental secret patterns (API keys, tokens in source) and ensure new dependencies were explicitly approved; run tests after security-sensitive edits.
